gm @dojo・52 !
This release contains major upgrades to our task generation process resulting in lower costs, better performance and better consistency. 

Validators can expect cheaper task generation, miners can expect sexier and more consistent tasks!

## Updates
### Dojo:
- updated task validation schema to support latest visual augment changes.
- fixed validator score back-up logic to address unstable weights after validator restarts.
- reduced size of send_score() payload to fix missing responses
### Synthetic-API:
- upgraded generation model improving code quality and reducing cost per task from $0.03~ to $0.01~
- introduced more concurrency reducing generation time from 10~ minutes to 1~ minute.
- improved reliability of auto-linting process
- refactored answer augmentation logic to become less predictable and more generalized to combat gamification.
- fixed bugs in few-shot examples that were causing frequent validation errors.
- enabled HFL support for upcoming future releases

```bash

make miner-pull
# restart miner

# or if you've chosen the decentralised method
```

We have committed the bulk of our attention and focus on the Dojo subnet, as most of the team is working on this subnet. Given the nature of how difficult of a topic we're addressing - it would mean that the effort we put into this cannot be directly translated into new features as easily as other subnets or other products. Keep in mind for every new feature we integrate we need to make sure that:

1. It is meaningful for us to collect such datasets (there is a business usecase for such datasets or there is a high-impact research outcome that could be generated as a result of collecting such datasets)

2. This gap can only be filled by humans and not exclusively AI. We do not discourage the use of AI pipelines to supplement the work done by human labellers as it helps to lower the costs of generating these outputs. But there would be something wrong if no humans are involved in the collection at all.

3. We will then need to build a custom pipeline to deliver these tasks to the miners and to collect the outputs, as opposed to most subnets that generally operate around a fixed sets of miner inputs and outputs.

4. We will have to find the best way of designing the incentive curve, such that we can incentivise miners to bring in the best human-generated datasets at the lowest cost, while also allowing new miners to onboard without getting heavily penalised because they do not have the advantage of optimising their human operations / AI pipelines. We will also need to directly correlate the score of the miners to the actual quality of the outputs which is theoretically impossible because if we knew the quality we would have used this as the ground truth instead of getting it from the miners. Which is why we're using proxies like synthetic ground truth and other scoring pipelines that we're currently researching.

This is the hardest topic in decentralised AI and once we unlock this we could enable a recursive, self-learning AI to supplement all subnets to beat SOTA.

Registration of the Contributor by the validator allows, to begin with, to attach a conditional number of the Contributor in the subnet, and then to keep track of the work of the Contributor and verify the rating of each Contributor.

Likewise this will allow the validator to assign for each Contributor a specific task from each Miner randomly.

Thus if the Contributor will be a human, then he will solve any task from any Miner, and if this will be a bot, then with foreign Miners it likely won't be able to connect.

At the same time, foreign Miners, most likely, will be interested in setting up checks for humanity. But these same foreign Miners will have to balance between decisions to pass the foreign Contributor or not, since this Miner will receive weight for the total number of correctly solved tasks.

In essence, any Miner can see the rating of any Contributor, which is established by the validator, and issue tasks for good Contributors, and for bad Contributors (without the presence of the Contributor's conditional immunity) not to issue tasks, but necessarily to announce about this (the total number of refusals to issue tasks also should influence the Miner's weight).

Thus if Contributors affiliated with one Miner correctly solve tasks (both foreign and their own), then this Miner receives additional weight, but if its Contributors poorly solve tasks, then it does not receive additional weight.

If a Miner sends the validator good answers only from its affiliated Contributors, and answers of foreign Contributors does not send (or intentionally distorts them), then it will receive less weight because on the whole it sent good answers less than other Miners who do not do this.

At the same time, if the Miner's Contributors intentionally do not solve foreign tasks, (or poorly solve foreign tasks) then this same Miner receives less weight because its Contributors lose rating when they do not solve foreign tasks.

Thus, in combination, we create conditions that force Miners to independently monitor that answers are given exclusively by humans with their own hands.

Additionally to these conditions, we could create an additional client-Contributor application for direct registration with the validator via a subscription key from the Miner. Thus the Miner sends the validator an application for registration of the Contributor, gives the subscription key to the Contributor, and then the Contributor itself registers with the validator.

After which the validator will be able directly, through this client, to receive data on the completion of tasks, which were assigned by it itself to the specific Contributor. Then compare the data received from the Miner and from the Contributor.

Hey @Dojo ! 👋

This release brings major improvements to validator task distribution and scoring mechanisms to enhance network security and fairness.

## What's Added

- Bucket-Based Task Distribution in which validator is randomizing miners into separate buckets, where each bucket receives different synthetic tasks.
- Temporarily disabled the quantity weight component to monitor the changes for bucket integration.
- env change - `DOJO_API_BASE_URL=https://dojo.network`

### Update and Restart Services
```bash
# Pull the updated repository
git pull

# Update .env
- remove VALIDATOR_API_BASE_URL
- add DOJO_API_BASE_URL=https://dojo.network

# Stop existing validator services if watchtower isn't enabled
make validator-down
make validator-pull

# Restart validator with improvements
make validator
```

## 🔧 Steps for Miners

```bash
# Pull the updated repository
git pull

# Update .env for miners who use our centralized api
DOJO_API_BASE_URL=https://dojo.network

# Stop existing validator services if watchtower isn't enabled
```
